Ordering Data

To get a numerical measure of an adverb’s order preference, I created a logistic random-effects model predicting, given two adverbs, which one came first in a given corpus occurrence. This model has random intercepts for the two adverbs, and no fixed effects. I constrained the correlation matrix of this model to be [[1,-1],[-1,1]] – that is, the two random intercepts are perfectly anti-correlated, encoding the prior knowledge that the order in which the two adverbs are entered into the model should be irrelevant to predicting the order found in the corpus. The fitted random slopes form an empirical measure of the ordering preference of adverbs: The slope for an adverb will be lower if it tends to appear earlier, and higher if it tends to appear later.

Compared to a simpler measure such as the overall proportion with which an adverb appears before or after another adverb in corpus sentences, this measure has the advantage that it controls for differences in frequency between adverbs.

The resulting measure has this distribution:

Here are some high-frequency adverbs, ordered by the rank (negative rank means that the adverb tends to occur earlier), with corpus frequencies (only counting occurrences where there is one other adverb):

Rating Study

I extracted sentences with pre-verbal adverbs from the dependency-parsed Ukwac. Due to automatic parsing, data are noisy, so more work would need to be done for a rigorous experiment.

First Questionnaire (48)

https://stanford.edu/~mhahn2/experiments/qp1/experiment/48-corpus/order-preference.html

Questions:

  1. Does the sentence make sense?
  2. Is the speaker saying that …?
  3. Does the highlighted word describe whether the speaker thinks that …?
  4. Does it describe how the fact that … relates to what was said before?
  5. Does it describe the way in which …?
  6. Does it describe the speaker's attitude towards the fact that …?

Here are violin diagrams for the responses:

Second Questionnaire (49)

https://stanford.edu/~mhahn2/experiments/qp1/experiment/49-corpus/order-preference.html

Some of the questions are as in the previous one, some are replaced by new ones:

  1. Does the sentence make sense?
  2. Is the speaker saying that …?
  3. Does the highlighted word comment on the fact that …?
  4. Does it describe how the speaker feels about the fact that …?
  5. Does it relate the sentence to things that might have been said earlier?
  6. Does it describe the way in which …?

Questionnaire vs Ordering Data

Here, I’m predicting the answers to each question from the two questionnaires from the adverb’s ordering preference, quantified by ranking adverbs as described above. In each graph, I’m showing a mixed effects model, and a plot of the responses as a function of the ordering preference rank.

Does the sentence make sense?

This question is just to get an idea of data quality and possibly later weeding out bad data. The responses are somewhat correlated with the ordering rank (t > 3) – not clear to me why this happens:

Does it describe the way in which …?

This is the strongest effect (both coefficient and t value) in these analyses, so I think it can be trusted: Adverbs that describe the action come later.

Does it describe the speaker's attitude towards the fact that …?

While the effect in the linear model doesn’t have strong evidence, the U-shaped curve is replicated in the `feelings’-question below. Maybe it has to do with clause-level vs VP-level adverbs – I’d expect there to be attitudinal adverbs in both groups. More work is needed to figure out whether this points to something real.

Subjectivity (43, 47)

https://stanford.edu/~mhahn2/experiments/qp1/experiment/43-subjectivity/order-preference.html

https://stanford.edu/~mhahn2/experiments/qp1/experiment/47-subjectivity/order-preference.html

This experiment is identical to the original Scontras et al. task collecting subjectivity ratings, but with adverbs.

Here, I test whether order preferences predict subjectivity ratings. At this point, there is no indication that subjectivity ratings correlate with order preferences:

Mutual Information

I quantified pointwise mutual information between adverbs and verbs by counting joint occurrences, disregarding any other words (context, the other adverb, and intervening material).

Mutual Information is predictive of distance to the verb, and even more of logarithmic distance:

Predicting Order from MI and Questionnaire Responses

Here, I’m predicting order preferences measured by the ranks from MI and questionnaire responses. All measures are averaged, so no random effects here. Among all models predicting rank from average MI + averaged responses, the one with the lowest p-value is:

## lm(formula = rank ~ mi + way + before, data = agg)

The correlation matrix shows that the effects contribute independently. I wouldn’t trust the relates to things said before' effect so much, but this shows that MI and the responses to thedescribes the way’ question independently predict ordering.

Conclusion

Adverb ordering is predicted to some extent by MI and the responses to the `describes the way in which …’ question.
